description_summary: The club aims to raise awareness of hospice care through educational activities like seminars, workshops, and mentorship. They plan to provide grief support and advanced care planning information to prepare members for volunteering or assisting loved ones. The club also organizes activities like making care packages, storybooks, and videos to bring comfort to hospice patients, with contributions counting towards volunteer hours.

name: Helping, Educating, and Learning Psychology (HELP)
meeting: Every week, on mondays, in room 3105, from 4PM-5PM
description: HELP is a non-profit club which stands for “Helping, Educating, and Learning Psychology”. HELP focuses on educating students while utilizing their assistance to help individuals facing psychological challenges. Every month, our club strives to learn more about a mental health disorder that impacts a large number of people. Trivia sessions will be held within the club to ensure that members foster a strong comprehensive understanding of the topic, so that they can adequately advocate for that mental health illness. After multiple thorough presentations, given by the officers, we will use this information to spread awareness, raise funds, and donate to the National Institute of Mental Health. NIMH is a federal agency that aims to transform the understanding and treatment of mental illnesses through rigorous clinical research to explore various treatment options and preventative measures. To accumulate the necessary funds, HELP has partnered up with a local boba store named Happy Lemon to organize monthly events, advocating for a specific mental health issue. In addition to this, we hope to educate students about healthy coping mechanisms to equip them with the ability to rationally analyze real life situations. We hope that students will not only apply these lessons to their own stressful lives, but also inspire others to do so.
description_summary: HELP is a non-profit club, "Helping, Educating, and Learning Psychology," dedicated to raising awareness about mental health disorders. Monthly activities include trivia sessions and presentations by officers to foster understanding. The club collaborates with a local boba store, Happy Lemon, to organize events and raise funds for the National Institute of Mental Health, supporting research and promoting healthy coping mechanisms among students.

name: Hindu Student Council
meeting: Lunch every first monday of the month.
description:
We will strive to provide opportunities to learn about the heritage and culture of Hindus while also raising awareness about the issues affecting Hindus, such as Hinduphobia or the persecution of Hindus. We derive our mission from the ancient Hindu scriptures; “sarve bhavantu sukhinah, sarve santu niramaya” — [May all be happy. May all be healthy]. “dharmo rakshati rakshitah” —[Dharma (righteousness), when protected and preserved, protects you].
Moreover, we want to create a safe space for people to find out what Hinduism means to them as an individual rather than something forced by their parents. In our experience, it is much easier with peers to be with you on that same journey and we would like to spread that. For the non-Hindus in our club, we want to share our faith because many people don't know how many facets there are and education is the best remedy. Additionally, the HSC family is always growing and will stay with our members past high school.
description_summary: The club aims to promote Hindu heritage and culture, raise awareness about issues like Hinduphobia, and draw inspiration from Hindu scriptures. It provides a safe space for individuals to explore Hinduism on a personal level, fostering a supportive community that extends beyond high school. Non-Hindus are encouraged to learn about the diverse facets of Hinduism through education.

name: History Day
meeting: Third Thursday of the month, room 1105
description: Our club helps students explore their interest in history by guiding them through creating a National History Day (NHD) project, conducting historical research, and writing historical papers. We will teach our members how to use primary resources, navigate archives, and cross-reference sources to find reliable information. Our club aims to foster an appreciation for history, develop critical thinking and analytical skills, and help our members develop strong writing and communication skills. We hope to help our members succeed in the National History Day competition as well as their personal research endeavors.
description_summary: Our club focuses on guiding students in history exploration through National History Day (NHD) projects, research, and paper writing. We teach primary resource usage, archive navigation, and source cross-referencing. Our goal is to nurture a passion for history, enhance critical thinking, and improve writing and communication skills. We aim to support members in NHD competition and personal research.

name: Igniting Dreams
meeting: once a month, on the first Tuesday during lunch, in room 9110
description: Igniting Dreams is a non-profit organization that aims to help underprivileged students through education. We create different types of handmade STEAM kits and through pairing with sister schools in Oakland, we’re able to give the community a chance to explore different fields while also providing a stronger foundation in learning. By having students work on these kits, we aspire to create a more diverse learning experience. Not only would DVHS students be able to apply their own knowledge, we would be able to expand on the different ways of learning for Oakland students. Education is something that should be accessible to everyone, and we hope to give underprivileged kids access to the same opportunities that more advantaged students have.
description_summary: Igniting Dreams, a non-profit, empowers underprivileged students through education. They craft STEAM kits, partnering with Oakland sister schools, offering diverse learning experiences. DVHS students apply knowledge and broaden learning for Oakland students, striving to make education accessible to all, bridging the opportunity gap.

name: Interact
meeting: first Wednesday of the month during lunch
description: Interact is a club promoted to helping high school students at Dougherty Valley strengthen their passion in volunteering and helping out our community. We provide them many volunteer opportunities throughout the entire year, including veteran crab feed, beach clean ups, city center events, and donation drives for organizations in need. Our motto is service above self, and our club has proudly exemplified this. We look forward to continuing to help out our community this year as part of Interact District 5160. We hope our club members create unforgettable bonds and friendships with Interactors all over the district.
description_summary: Interact Club at Dougherty Valley High School is dedicated to community service. They offer various volunteer opportunities, such as crab feeds, beach cleanups, city events, and donation drives. Their motto is "service above self," and they are committed to serving the community as part of Interact District 5160, fostering bonds and friendships among members.

name: Jazz
meeting: Twice a week on Wednesdays, during access in the green room and after school in the band room
description: Jazz Club is a vibrant, performance-oriented community of musicians interested in the art of jazz music. Our main purpose is to bring more awareness to the genre of jazz and allow all members of our club to develop skills that they would not be able to obtain anywhere else. We do this through weekly meetings where we teach new concepts of harmony and improvisation, and rehearse for upcoming performances. Some of the locations we have performed include numerous local senior centers and school events. On occasion, we even get gigs at restaurants. Many members have used the constructive environment provided by our club to improve, audition for, and get into our school jazz band and even prestigious honor band programs. Committed members such as these, allow our club to prosper and grow with each coming year, as we are sure to do this year.
description_summary: Jazz Club is a dynamic community of musicians passionate about jazz music. It hosts weekly meetings focusing on harmony, improvisation, and rehearsals for performances at local senior centers, schools, and restaurants. Members benefit from skill development, often securing positions in school jazz bands and honor programs, contributing to the club's growth.

name: Key
meeting: Once a month, on the second Tuesday, in room 2201
description: Key club is the world's largest student-led international service organization. Key Club International has established clubs in over 40 countries, and is proud of being home to more than 250,000 members. Key Club International achieves a tremendous 12 million hours of service each year. Key Club aims to not only provide members with opportunities to be involved in community service, but to also provide members with opportunities to build character and develop leadership. Key Club may not make keys, but we definitely open doors to new pathways and opportunities for everyone.
description_summary: Key Club is a global student-led service organization with 250,000 members in 40+ countries. They achieve 12 million service hours annually, focusing on community involvement, character building, and leadership development, offering pathways to new opportunities for all.

name: Kids Against Hunger
meeting: Once a month, on the first Friday, room 9103
description: Kids Against Hunger is an organization that seeks to combat hunger by packing and distributing meals all over the world. Members will volunteer at packing events in the Kids Against Hunger warehouse where they will help provide a basic human necessity for the impoverished and malnourished. Through each packing event, at least one thousand meals will be shipped to hungry children in Haiti, Ukraine, and more. Our club would greatly appreciate anyone interested in contributing to this greater cause to not only aid these people in need but also strengthen our community. Join us to feed families around the world and around the corner.
description_summary: Kids Against Hunger is an organization dedicated to fighting hunger by organizing meal-packing events worldwide. Volunteers help pack meals in their warehouse, providing a vital necessity to the impoverished. Each event results in sending at least one thousand meals to hungry children in various countries, including Haiti and Ukraine. Join us to support this cause and strengthen our community by feeding families globally and locally.

name: Korean American Student Association
meeting: Once a month on the first Monday, in room 4106
description: The DVHS Korean American Student Association club strives to spread Korean culture to many students at DVHS. While the name of the club refers to Korean American students, our club is open to anyone who is interested in Korean culture, media, and/or  traditions. Like last year, we plan to have exciting bonding activities for anyone who is Korean or is interested in Korean culture and to also spread the Korean language as well. We hope to continue some of the fun activities such as dalgona coffee making and K-movie watching, and hope that the members of this club will also strive to further spread Korean culture, media, and food at DVHS.
description_summary: The DVHS Korean American Student Association club aims to promote Korean culture to all DVHS students, regardless of their background. The club organizes bonding activities like dalgona coffee making and K-movie watching. They also focus on spreading the Korean language and hope members will actively contribute to sharing Korean culture, media, and food at DVHS.

name: Korean Music and Dance
meeting: Last Friday of every month during lunch in 1209; 4:00pm at front of commons table, every Friday
description: Our club is unique in that we provide an environment for students to not only share their interests in Kpop, but also turn their interests into a skillful hobby. During our lunch meetings, we offer a wide variety of events including Kpop related games, competitions, and lessons on Korean history and culture. Students gather to participate in fun events while expanding their knowledge of the Kpop industry. At our weekly Friday dance meeting, we provide students with dance lessons, performance opportunities, and a collaborative team with a shared passion for Korean music allowing students to grow their performative abilities. However, we strive to maintain an environment that is encouraging, patient, and stress free. We emphasize that these classes are for members of all dancing abilities. Through live performances and Music Video covers, our members receive the opportunity to demonstrate their abilities and take pride in their skills. Since our music videos are completely self-produced, members and officers also receive the opportunity to utilize their videography, video editing, and music production skills.
description_summary: Our unique club offers students a chance to explore their interests in Kpop while honing their skills. We host lunch meetings with Kpop games, competitions, and Korean culture lessons. Our Friday dance meetings provide dance lessons, performance opportunities, and a collaborative environment for students passionate about Korean music. We emphasize inclusivity for all dance abilities and offer chances for members to showcase their skills through self-produced music videos, fostering creativity.

name: Latinx
meeting: Once a month on the first tuesday of every month in Mr Clemente’s room
description: The Latinx club aims to help educate students about Latinx culture and have an environment where all can come together and learn about what makes Latinx countries unique and how they impact the world. Our goal with this club is to have an environment that is inclusive of all that can help teach the Latinx heritage to students at Dougherty Valley in order to have cross cultural understanding and unity in order to bring all Wildcats together regardless of their backgrounds. Throughout the year we will promote different components of the Latinx heritage in order to celebrate the diversity in the community. We want to be able to build bridges between all cultures. In doing so, we are able to unify many different cultures by learning about others and their heritage, and through cultural exchanges between multiple backgrounds, which ultimately fosters a richer tapestry of diversity at Dougherty Valley High School by making our school more understanding of one another. We want to teach students about important Latinx figures as well and have a place where everyone's voices can be heard. We also want to give back to the Latinx community by helping out and doing community service in order to better society.
description_summary: The Latinx club at Dougherty Valley aims to promote Latinx culture and foster cross-cultural understanding. They organize activities to celebrate Latinx heritage, educate students about important figures, and engage in community service to benefit the Latinx community and create a more inclusive and diverse school environment.

name: Leukemia & Lymphoma Society
meeting: Once a month on the 2nd Tuesday
description: DVHS Leukemia & Lymphoma Society is a fundraising club focused on raising awareness to support blood cancer patients. We are partnered with the world's biggest organization fighting blood cancers today. Members of the club get volunteer hours and CSF points; they get to interact with professionals who work in the medical field, researchers, and blood cancer patients; they also have the opportunity to share their own research and ideas through blogs and social media posts. Not only that, but members support a cause that improves millions of lives. We hope you'll become a part of this club and the DVHS LLS community. If you are interested in joining, fill out our interest form: tinyurl.com/DVHSLLSINTEREST Have any questions? Join our remind @dvhs-lls or email us at dvhs.lls@gmail.com; Support us by following our instagram @dvhs.lls
description_summary: The DVHS Leukemia & Lymphoma Society is a fundraising club that raises awareness and supports blood cancer patients. Club members earn volunteer hours and CSF points, interact with medical professionals and researchers, and can share their research and ideas through blogs and social media.

name: Liberty in North Korea
meeting: Once a month, third Fridays, in room 3114
description: DVHS LiNK is the DVHS chapter of the non-profit organization Liberty in North Korea (LiNK). LiNK was founded to provide funds for North Korean refugees on their journey from escaping to settling down in other countries through fundraisers held by LiNK and its high school chapters. At DV, we have and will continue to hold fundraisers to aid LiNK in providing connections and services for North Korean refugees. In past years, we have held fundraisers with Krispy Kreme, T4 and Teaspoons, in which total funds raised were donated to LiNK. This year, we plan to hold many more fundraisers to continue taking part in sponsoring one's escape to liberty.
description_summary: DVHS LiNK is the DVHS chapter of the non-profit organization Liberty in North Korea (LiNK). They host fundraisers, including partnerships with Krispy Kreme, T4, and Teaspoons, to provide funds for North Korean refugees on their journey to freedom and resettlement in other countries. Their goal is to continue sponsoring escapes to liberty through ongoing fundraisers.

name: Linguistics
meeting: Every other Wednesday in Room 4210
description: We are a club dedicated to the study and learning of human language. We seek to provide members with opportunities to not only learn new languages, but learn about their similarities, differences and their features in order to become more aware or the world around us. We end up having some really interesting conversations about how languages evolved, how a language reflects a culture, and how everything is connected. We also have fun activities such as games and projects. Last year, we got the opportunity to speak with Dr. Paul Frommer (USC professor who invented Na'avi language for James Cameron's avatar) and were able to gain a lot of insight about how to go about constructing a language. If any of the above sounds cool or interesting to you, you should definitely join our club!
description_summary: This club is dedicated to the study of human language. Members learn various languages, explore their similarities and differences, and discuss language evolution and cultural reflection. Fun activities, games, and projects are part of the experience. They also had a special guest, Dr. Paul Frommer, who shared insights on constructing languages. Join for a unique language journey!

name: Literary Alliance
meeting: once a month - weekly, multiple days, online and room 1207 (email for inquiries!)
description: DVHS Literary Alliance is dedicated to fostering global literacy and helping children develop a lifelong love for reading. The club involves two main branches: Build-a-Book and the African Library Project. Build-a-Book is a creative writing mentorship program for elementary and middle school students. Members who participate in this program serve as mentors (2 high school mentors per mentee) and guide these students through the entire writing process, culminating into every mentee's own book. Mentors are able to gain leadership experience and volunteer hours throughout the school year-long program.The African Library Project is a non-profit organization that works to create, improve, and sustain libraries in African communities. ALP connects North American volunteers with partners in Africa throughout the year to organize book drives. In our 2020-2021 book drive, we sent over 1,200 books to Malawi!
description_summary: The DVHS Literary Alliance is a club with two main activities: Build-a-Book and the African Library Project. Build-a-Book is a creative writing mentorship program where high school members guide elementary and middle school students in creating their own books, gaining leadership and volunteer experience. The club also partners with the African Library Project to send books to African communities, sending over 1,200 books to Malawi in 2020-2021.

name: Livin' It Up
meeting: First Tuesday of every month, room 1212
description: Our mission is to help our school community make healthy choices so you can become your happiest and healthiest. We focus on helping you figure out how to reduce stress and be careful about what goes inside your body. We will invite guest speakers to inspire healthy lifestyles, teach you how to read food labels, make healthy recipes, and learn how to manage stress through high school and beyond. Each meeting will address an aspect of healthy living. A part of living healthy includes our diet, so we'll be making easy snacks in our meetings. Come join us to see how being healthy can be delicious!!!
description_summary: The club's mission is to promote healthy choices within the school community. Activities include guest speakers, food label reading, healthy recipe preparation, stress management, and snack-making. The focus is on overall well-being and the enjoyment of healthy living.

name: Love & Second Chances
meeting: On the first monday of every month, in room 9110
description: DV Love & Second Chances, affiliated with the Bay Area NPO Love & Second Chances, aims to improve the lives of rescued homeless animals through willing high school volunteers. LSC volunteers help death-row, abused, and neglected dogs find forever homes at the local LSC rescue.
description_summary: DV Love & Second Chances, affiliated with the Bay Area NPO Love & Second Chances, aims to improve the lives of rescued homeless animals through willing high school volunteers. LSC volunteers help death-row, abused, and neglected dogs find forever homes at the local LSC rescue.

name: Machine Learning
meeting: Once a week, on Thursdays, afterschool on Zoom
description: The DVHS Machine Learning Club seeks to educate students on the fundamentals of artificial intelligence and machine learning by exposing them to a variety of topics such as computer vision, natural language processing, and generative AI. We give lessons on both the theory and code behind these topics, as well as interactive labs for members to apply their knowledge. People from all experience levels are welcome to join this club and glean a new perspective on machine learning. The ultimate goal of the Machine Learning Club is to strengthen foundational programming skills and cultivate interest and prowess in artificial intelligence and machine learning software development.
description_summary: The DVHS Machine Learning Club educates students in artificial intelligence and machine learning through lessons and interactive labs covering computer vision, natural language processing, and generative AI. All experience levels are welcome, with a focus on strengthening programming skills and fostering interest in AI and ML software development.

name: Marching Orchestra
meeting: I plan on meeting every Monday Wednesday, and Saterday in the DVHS parking lot (infront of the school).
description: Our mission is to spread joy and comfort through the art of the performing arts. As noted by the CDC, suicide is the second leading cause of death for young adults; in other terms, us. Given Dougherty´s competitive attitude in academics, the chance of death is high. My friend who was a senior committed suicide through Dougherty. He was energetic and above all a kind person. He couldn't see the light. Although I am filled with anger and negative emotions of losing him, the joy of my life, I learned that I can not trap myself in the past knowing that there are people who feel the same way as my friend. Given my love of performing arts and the awards I received, I feel that this club is a necessity for our community. We will accomplish this goal by holding weekly rehearsals where musicians and artists are to practice their respective instrument(s) where they are to produce awesome pieces of film and music. Below are the 2 groups and their individual goals and plans. Regarding music, we plan to create a marching band and a full orchestra. Our marching band will perform at football games. Either in halftime or after the game. We believe that music has the power to invoke motivation that will empower people.  We hope to collaborate with our school’s glorious cheerleaders to make them dance in the act of the role of the color guard(s).
description_summary: This performing arts club plans to achieve this by holding weekly rehearsals for musicians and artists to create compelling music and film. They aim to establish a marching band and a full orchestra, with performances at football games, believing that music can inspire and empower individuals. Collaboration with the school's cheerleaders is also envisioned.

name: Math
meeting: Every Wednesday after school, in room 3209
description: Math Club aims to foster enthusiasm for math through introducing members to new mathematical ideas during meetings and promoting pre-collegiate math competitions. Students of all math backgrounds and experiences are welcome to join. Our weekly meetings cover a variety of topics and activities, including AMC preparation, relay rounds, Kahoot, For the Win! tournaments, team practices for upcoming competitions, and guest speaker events with Math Club officer alums. We provide information, training, and sign-ups for relevant competitions, which may include but are not limited to the American Math Competitions, Mathleague, Berkeley Math Tournament, and Stanford Math Tournament. Math Club values concentrated discussions, problem-solving, creative thinking, and eventual application toward real-world problems. From Math Club, students will gain intellectual and lifestyle mentalities that will help them eventually tackle worldwide problems and work productively with colleagues.
description_summary: The Math Club focuses on fostering math enthusiasm through various activities like AMC preparation, relay rounds, Kahoot, tournaments, team practices, and guest speaker events with alumni officers. It welcomes students of all math backgrounds, providing training and sign-ups for competitions like AMC, Mathleague, Berkeley Math Tournament, and Stanford Math Tournament. The club values concentrated discussions, problem-solving, creative thinking, and real-world problem-solving skills to prepare students for future challenges.

name: Math National Honors Society
meeting: first Wednesday of the month
description: Math National Honor Society promotes scholarship in and enjoyment and understanding of mathematics among high school students. We recognize and encourage students who enjoy and excel in mathematics. We’re a club committed to enhancing student ability to work with others, to conduct independent research, and learn the qualities of industry, initiative, and reliability.
description_summary: Math National Honor Society promotes scholarship in and enjoyment and understanding of mathematics among high school students. We recognize and encourage students who enjoy and excel in mathematics. We’re a club committed to enhancing student ability to work with others, to conduct independent research, and learn the qualities of industry, initiative, and reliability.

name: MedQuest
meeting: First 3 Tuesdays of the month. Each week except last week of the month.
description: MedQuest is a high school club dedicated to igniting the curiosity and passion of students for medical exploration and research. Through a well-structured meeting schedule, it offers a diverse range of activities, including dissecting real medical cases, conducting research projects, and exploring various medical fields, while also spotlighting different medical careers each month. Members collaborate to unravel complex medical cases, develop impactful research projects for state science fairs, and explore diverse medical topics that shed light on potential career paths. This club fosters critical thinking, research skills, and career awareness among members while providing valuable opportunities to learn from professionals, develop teamwork and communication skills, and create lasting connections with like-minded peers. MedQuest provides a supportive and enriching environment where students can pursue their passion for medicine and research.
description_summary: MedQuest, a high school club, offers diverse activities like dissecting medical cases, research projects, and exploring medical fields. It spotlights different medical careers monthly, fostering critical thinking, research skills, and career awareness. Members collaborate on complex cases, develop impactful research for science fairs, and build connections with peers and professionals, creating an enriching environment for medical exploration.

name: MedShare
meeting: Once a month on the last Thursday.
description: DVHS Medshare's goal is to improve the livelihoods of people across the planet by providing medical supplies for under-resourced countries. Our primary message is to promote sustainability while improving quality of life by collecting sterile medical supplies that would otherwise go to waste in the US. Our club serves its goals by hosting many packing events throughout the school year, organizing drives and fundraising money. Our club has fulfilled its mission by providing opportunities for students to make a difference in developing countries and cultivate their understanding of medical waste while gaining a better understanding of the logistics of the medical field.
description_summary: DVHS Medshare aims to enhance global livelihoods through sustainable practices. They collect surplus sterile medical supplies in the US and redistribute them to under-resourced countries. Activities include packing events, drives, and fundraising. The club empowers students to impact developing nations and gain insights into medical waste management and logistics.

name: Mission Coral
meeting: Once a month, on the second Wednesday during lunch, in room 2101
description: Mission Coral is a club dedicated to educating and inspiring student action on coral reef and environmental preservation. We host related fundraisers, donation drives, and volunteering opportunities. We do community work, cleaning up beaches, trails, parks, and the school campus, as well as offer many opportunities and activities outside of school. As a club, we strive to interactively educate our own members and other students on concerning environmental threats and ways to be involved in helping our planet’s ecosystems.
description_summary: Mission Coral is a club focused on coral reef and environmental preservation. They organize fundraisers, donation drives, and community clean-up events. The club offers various activities and opportunities for students to get involved in environmental conservation and education.

name: Mobile Application Development
meeting: First and third Thursday during lunch, in room 4204; Second and fourth Friday after school on Zoom call.
description: The Mobile Application Development Club (MAD) is a club to help students create their own mobile application and teach them the development process of creating an app. The ultimate end goal is to have students get their app published on the iOS App Store and Android Google Play Store by the end of the school year. Through this journey of helping students create a mobile app, we aim to improve student collaboration and communication. We foster a place for like-minded individuals to work together, share ideas, and encourage teamwork. We also want to increase the amount of learning opportunities for the students at DVHS, and create a network of empowering coders and aspiring mobile app developers. Even if you have no experience in coding, we will guide you through the whole process. We are all here to learn from each other. With this club, you have opportunities to gain necessary experience for a career in computer science. Additionally, we will be hosting hackathons with cash prizes. These hackathons are a great way to practice your coding and teamwork skills. There is also a huge conference where we are inviting multiple mobile app developers and CEOs of tech companies. This is a great way to expand your network and potentially gain an internship opportunity. This conference will have a formal dress code with various events to win cash prizes.
description_summary: The Mobile Application Development Club (MAD) focuses on helping students create mobile apps and aims to get their apps published on iOS and Android stores. It promotes collaboration, communication, and learning opportunities among students. MAD offers coding guidance, hackathons with cash prizes, and a networking conference with tech professionals for career growth and internships.

name: Mock Trial
meeting: every Tuesday in Mr. Shieh's room (3110)
description: Mock Trial is a competition- based club in which students simulate court cases, prepare questioning based on case packets, and argue as either the prosecution or defense. The competition takes place in a real court with professional judges. Roles consist of pre-trial attorneys, trial attorneys, and witnesses. Performances will be graded based on quality of questioning, acting abilities of witnesses, and the overall ability to truly emulate a court setting. Participating will prepare you for a future career in law, improve your public speaking, and teach you how to be quick on your feet! But most importantly, you’ll make new friends and have a lot of fun! Join Mock Trial!
description_summary: Mock Trial is a competitive club where students engage in courtroom simulations, taking on roles such as attorneys and witnesses. They argue cases before professional judges in a real court setting, emphasizing quality questioning and acting skills. Participation enhances legal career prospects, public speaking, and quick thinking, all while fostering new friendships and enjoyment. Join Mock Trial for an exciting experience!

name: Model United Nations
meeting: Every Thursday 4-5 PM in the Library
description: Dougherty Valley Model United Nations is a competitive club that teaches students about diplomacy, public speaking, research, and leadership through an educational simulation of the United Nations. Club meetings encounter frequent drills that help students become a more articulate orator and a more confident public speaker. DVMUN members utilize the skills they learn to compete at prestigious tournaments such as Stanford MUN, Berkeley MUN, and others. Members frequently place first, second, and third at these highly competitive conferences, and DVMUN was named an Outstanding Large Delegation by UC Davis MUN in 2022. In addition to local tournaments, members also get a chance to go on travel conferences to places like USC and Harvard. Besides actively competing, DVMUN also has a close and light-hearted community full of awesome people. It is not only a great club to learn essential skills and compete at prestigious conferences, but it is also a great place to meet new people who share similar passions for international relations and public speaking.
description_summary: Dougherty Valley Model United Nations (DVMUN) is a club that focuses on diplomacy, public speaking, research, and leadership through United Nations simulations. The club holds frequent drills to enhance students' oratory and public speaking skills. DVMUN excels at prestigious tournaments like Stanford MUN and Berkeley MUN, often securing top rankings. DVMUN also fosters a vibrant and friendly community for individuals interested in international relations and public speaking.

name: Music
meeting: Twice a month, 1st and 3rd Monday, in 3204 (Sra.Barahona's Room) during LUNCH
description: Music Club is where all musicians and music lovers can come together and create and experience music together.  We are open to everyone, from beginners to the advanced.  All we require is that you have a joy for music!  We focus on creating a positive learning environment where members can make new friends and experiences, and also grow their musical skills throughout the year.  To accomplish this, we have many fun activities and guest speakers designed specifically for our members to try out new styles of music, enhance their own creativity, hear other's music, get feedback on their own songs, and have many opportunities to perform their own songs and gain recognition for their hard work, all while having fun!
description_summary: The Music Club welcomes musicians and music enthusiasts of all levels. It offers a positive learning environment for members to create music, make friends, and grow their skills. The club organizes various activities, guest speakers, and opportunities to explore different music styles, enhance creativity, receive feedback, and perform, fostering a fun and supportive community.

name: Music Service
meeting: Typically once or twice a month in room PA
description: We're a club focused on providing music to those in the community who might not have limited access to music resources. Because of this, our main club activities include hosting one-on-one lessons between our club members tutoring middle schoolers and elementary schoolers around the school district.
description_summary: We're a club focused on providing music to those in the community who might not have limited access to music resources. Because of this, our main club activities include hosting one-on-one lessons between our club members tutoring middle schoolers and elementary schoolers around the school district.

name: Muslim Student Association
meeting: Every Friday during lunch
description: The Muslim Student Association fosters a robust Muslim community at DVHS, promoting unity between Muslims and non-Muslims. Weekly Friday prayers are inclusive, allowing non-Muslims to attend and even participate. Beyond, we organize enjoyable off-campus events with other MSAs.
description_summary: The Muslim Student Association fosters a robust Muslim community at DVHS, promoting unity between Muslims and non-Muslims. Weekly Friday prayers are inclusive, allowing non-Muslims to attend and even participate. Beyond, we organize enjoyable off-campus events with other MSAs.

name: NAMI
meeting: Once a month on thursdays in room 1109
description: NAMI Club is open to everyone. We provide support for students who are living with mental illness or have a loved one with mental illness. We provide information on school and community resources, encourage people to recognize early signs of mental illness, encourage students who are having mental health issues to think about getting help, work to end the stigma that surrounds mental illness, create an inclusive, safe and supportive school environment, and let students know there is help available if they need it.
description_summary: The NAMI Club offers support and resources for students dealing with mental illness. They promote awareness, early recognition of mental health issues, and ending the stigma. The club fosters a safe and inclusive school environment, emphasizing the availability of help for those in need.

name: National Art Honor Society
meeting: Once a month, on the first Wednesday, in room 4103
description: National Art Honor Society (NAHS) promotes the highest standards in art scholarship, character, and service by bringing art education to the attention of the school community. Student artists are provided opportunities to showcase their creative abilities in a space where both personal and artistic ambitions are nurtured.  Dougherty's NAHS strives to bridge the gap between the art community and outside organizations through design and tutoring services. Members involved in NAHS are encourages to invest service hours outside of school and give back to the community with their talents.
description_summary: The National Art Honor Society (NAHS) focuses on promoting art scholarship, character, and service. It provides student artists with opportunities to showcase their creativity, nurtures personal and artistic ambitions, and bridges the gap between the art community and outside organizations through design and tutoring services. NAHS members are encouraged to invest service hours in the community using their talents.

name: National English Honors Society
meeting: Last Wednesday of every month during lunch (additional meetings may be added in between), in room 1214
description: The Dougherty Valley National English Honor Society works to create a community for those who are passionate for the literary arts, reading and writing, and related careers, and giving them the opportunities to use the English language to deliver impact to local and international communities. Our club promotes more activity and passion for literary arts, reading, and careers relating to literature and language. We will host multiple events and organize activities that encourage students to explore various aspects of language arts, learn about possible careers, and showcase their talents through contests and club projects. We will also be using our skills in language arts to reach out to the community through service projects to increase the accessibility to education and spread awareness about social issues.
description_summary: The Dougherty Valley National English Honor Society fosters a literary community, focusing on literary arts, reading, and language-related careers. They organize events, activities, and contests to inspire passion for language arts, explore career opportunities, and showcase talents. Additionally, they engage in community service projects to promote education accessibility and raise awareness of social issues.

name: National Honors Society
meeting: Biweekly Executive Board Meetings in Room 1220, New Member Orientation Meeting once per semester in Room 1220, and Full Club Meetings 2-3 times per semester in the theater
description: NHS focuses on filling service needs at Dougherty, in our neighborhood and in our surrounding area. Our goal is to get you involved in different aspects of life around you and help give back to all of your communities!
description_summary: NHS focuses on filling service needs at Dougherty, in our neighborhood and in our surrounding area. Our goal is to get you involved in different aspects of life around you and help give back to all of your communities!

name: National Ocean Science Bowl
meeting: Twice a month, every other Friday at lunch, in Mrs. Dreon's room
description: We strive to educate others about the ocean  inspire others to love ocean science! This club is designed to prepare club members to compete in the annual National Ocean Science Bowl and Sea Lion Bowl, as well as other ocean-related activities.
description_summary: We strive to educate others about the ocean  inspire others to love ocean science! This club is designed to prepare club members to compete in the annual National Ocean Science Bowl and Sea Lion Bowl, as well as other ocean-related activities.

name: National Science Bowl
meeting: every Wednesday
description: The Department of Energy (DOE) created the National Science Bowl in 1991 to encourage students to excel in mathematics and science and to pursue careers in these fields. More than 335,000 students have participated in the National Science Bowl® throughout its 33-year history, and it is one of the nation’s largest science competitions. Our club will have a recruitment process and create qualified teams that will be compete for a spot at the National Science Bowl in Washington, D.C. in Spring 2024.
description_summary: The Department of Energy (DOE) established the National Science Bowl in 1991 to promote math and science excellence among students. Over 335,000 students have taken part in this prestigious science competition, which our club aims to join by forming qualified teams through a recruitment process. These teams will compete for a spot at the National Science Bowl in Washington, D.C. in Spring 2024.

name: Pen and Platform
meeting: Every Tuesday after school (4:10 pm) in room 4102
description: The Pen and Platform Society is devoted to carving out a creative space for writers, in DVHS's STEM focused community. Here, we promote the voices of DV writers, get students published in literary magazines and journals, and even help them enter the vast world of writing for the first time. The Pen and Platform Society empowers all voices. We treasure diversity in our works, and are looking to uplift stories about inequality and injustice in today's world. Every Tuesday after school, we will be holding feedback circles, open mics, writing contests, writing workshops and much more. By the end of the year, we hope to create a space where DV's writers can truly come together and improve their writing as a group.
description_summary: The Pen and Platform Society at DVHS is a creative club for writers in the STEM community. They support DV writers by publishing their work, fostering diversity, and addressing inequality and injustice. Activities include feedback circles, open mics, contests, workshops, and more, aiming to create a collaborative space for writers to improve together.

name: Period
meeting: The club will meet twice a month, on a Tuesday during lunch in room 1204.
description: PERIOD is a nonprofit organization that is fighting to end period poverty and period stigma through service, education, and advocacy. PERIOD.DV is Dougherty Valley’s chapter of PERIOD, and among one of many chapters across the globe.The service aspect of this club consists of donating menstrual products to those in need, we at DV do this primarily through the power of donation drives. During donation drives we donate sanitary products (pads and tampons) to local shelters and other organizations. As for education we host educational seminars at our meetings, during these workshops we discuss the stigma around menstruation and increase awareness about menstrual health. Finally advocacy, we advocate for systemic change to battle period poverty. This comes in the form of creating change at DV which in 2023 we did, we worked with admin to make heating pads available in the nurse's office! We at PERIOD believe all menstruators deserve safe access to period products.
description_summary: PERIOD.DV, a chapter of the nonprofit organization PERIOD, focuses on combating period poverty and stigma. The club conducts donation drives to provide menstrual products to those in need, hosts educational seminars to raise awareness about menstruation, and advocates for systemic change, such as making heating pads available in the nurse's office to ensure safe access to period products.

name: Persian Culture
meeting: once a month during lunch
description: our club is a place for people of all ethnic backgrounds to get together and learn about persian culture as well as have a safe space in general
description_summary: The club provides a welcoming environment for individuals of diverse backgrounds to explore Persian culture and offers a safe space for community bonding and cultural education.

name: Philosophy
meeting: Twice a month, every other Monday, in room 1115
description: DVHS Philosophy Club is a club centered around intellectual curiosity and philosophical discussions. We explore questions concerning a broad range of subjects, from ethics to religion to consciousness. Club meetings will consist of structured Socratic seminars centered around discussions of philosophical concepts. Additionally, Philosophy Club aims to provide members with the opportunity to participate in the National High School Ethics Bowl (NHSEB), a national team competition on ethical debate.
description_summary: The DVHS Philosophy Club focuses on intellectual curiosity and philosophical discussions, exploring topics like ethics, religion, and consciousness. Club meetings involve structured Socratic seminars for philosophical discussions and offer members a chance to compete in the National High School Ethics Bowl for ethical debates.

name: Photography
meeting: once a month, every second Wednesday during lunch, room 4206
description: The Photography Club is a group of people who focus on using creativity to capture and freeze a moment and create a memory that lasts forever. The club aims to create opportunities to participate in photography adventures and discussions on the art form with like-minded friends.  Every meeting, we will be focusing on one aspect or technique of photography. Some examples include portraits, nature photography, astrophotography on a broader spectrum, but in order for members to improve their skills on these larger aspects, we will also be providing lessons on the smaller details, such as lighting, angles, background, etc. These lessons will be provided by the club officers providing a concise slide-show type “lecture” which will be followed by hands-on work where the members will be able to practice the skill themself. We will be bringing one camera to teach the topics but members are free to use their own device/camera if they wish to do so. Our club meetings will consist of photo-walks, lectures on a specific skill, hands-on workshops, and, one of the best ways for our members to learn and improve their photography skills. A tentative plan is to hold online meetings with professional photographers once every couple of meetings to provide their own insights and techniques.
description_summary: The Photography Club is a creative group focused on capturing moments and creating lasting memories through photography. They organize activities such as photo-walks, skill lectures, hands-on workshops, and online meetings with professional photographers. Members can improve their photography skills by exploring various aspects like portraits, nature, and astrophotography, with lessons on lighting, angles, and more.

name: Physics
meeting: Every Wednesday during Lunch, room 1108
description: DVHS Physics Club is the perfect place for all physics enthusiasts. The club consists of weekly seminars, lectures, and game-style competitions among members that aim to foster a deeper understanding of physics concepts. It isn't just an extension of physics class – we'll explore high school topics while also discussing subjects like electromagnetism, quantum physics, astrophysics, etc. At the same time, the club also offers opportunities for college accolades and awards in physics through national competitions such as USAPhO and Physics Bowl. It is a place to form connections with like-minded individuals and express your love for physics. It's low stakes – no signup or commitment required, just bring your interest and open mind to our next meeting!
description_summary: The DVHS Physics Club offers a vibrant space for physics enthusiasts. They organize weekly seminars, lectures, and competitive games to enhance physics understanding. Beyond high school topics, they explore electromagnetism, quantum physics, astrophysics, and more. The club provides opportunities for national physics competitions like USAPhO and Physics Bowl, fostering connections among like-minded individuals. No commitment is needed; just join with an open mind.

name: PiTech
meeting: Once a month, on the first Monday during lunch, in room 4201
description: The PiTech club is dedicated teaching DVHS students the fundamentals Raspberry Pi. The club is focused on hands-on exploration, which is possible with our provided Raspberry Pi 4GB kits. The curriculum covers the basics of Raspberry Pi hardware, programming, and project development. We also heavily focus on providing members with individual projects, in order to, test club member’s practical skills and build up their problem-solving abilities and familiarity with Raspberry Pi.
description_summary: The PiTech club at DVHS is dedicated to teaching students the fundamentals of Raspberry Pi through hands-on exploration using provided Raspberry Pi 4GB kits. The curriculum covers hardware, programming, and project development, emphasizing individual projects to enhance practical skills and problem-solving abilities with Raspberry Pi.

name: Plate to Planet
meeting: Once a month, Thursday Lunch, in Ms. Lau's room
description: Our club intends to tackle issues surrounding food: from food inequality to climate change, food remains to be a central factor in solving global dilemmas. Through this club, we intend to spread awareness about the causes of food insecurity and food inequality in countries around the world, as well as educating the public on the ecological impacts of food production, sustainable food production and how to limit one's carbon footprint without cutting ubiquitously enjoyed food items from one's diet. Our club intends to highlight the growing disparity between the availability of food in different regions of demographic or socioeconomic backgrounds, as well as contributing to solve these problems through hosting food drives and events and donating to local charities, providing food to those who do not have access to those.
description_summary: The club focuses on addressing food-related issues such as inequality and climate change. It aims to raise awareness about global food insecurity and ecological impacts of food production, while promoting sustainable practices. The club organizes food drives, events, and donates to local charities to alleviate disparities in food access.

name: Politics Club
meeting: Once a week, on Wednesday, in room 1103.
description: The goal of the political debate club is to provide the Dougherty Valley community with a location where they can freely express their opinions on political, economic, and social issues that take place in the United States and globally. The idea is that if the club doesn’t focus too much on assignments or projects and instead focuses on fostering respectful and healthy conversation among DVHS students, the club can serve as a way to connect the community more and create a more open-minded school environment where important issues are discussed more freely. The most important thing we want to accomplish is to increase our membership; the more people that we can get involved in the club, the more people become interested in what is being discussed, the more input there is in the conversation about these issues, the more engagement and open discussions about these issues without those discussions being disrespectful or anxiety-inducing. It is also a place of learning, where students who have little to no background in politics are still able to come together and form an opinion by learning about global current events. This can bridge the gap and make politics seem less intimidating and more of a topic where people are open to agree, disagree, learn, and grow.
description_summary: The political debate club at Dougherty Valley aims to facilitate open and respectful discussions on political, economic, and social issues in the United States and globally. Their primary goal is to increase membership to encourage more engagement and diverse perspectives. It also serves as a learning platform for students with limited political knowledge, making politics more approachable for growth and understanding.

name: Power Engin California
meeting: Last Wednesday of every month in room 9111 during Lunch.
description: Our club is focused on improving the literacy of students around the world. Some of our main focuses is donating books to people who often don't have many to read and improve their knowledge. We also have partnered with ENGin to run a program allowing high-school students to talk English for 1 hour a week with Ukrainian students looking to improve their English. We meet once every month to discuss new initiatives and new goals to tackle to help us reach our goal of making reading, writing, and speaking English easier for everyone.
description_summary: The club's activities include donating books to underserved communities, partnering with ENGin for English language exchange programs between high-school and Ukrainian students, and holding monthly meetings to plan initiatives for improving literacy and English proficiency worldwide.

name: Powerlifting
meeting: Every Thursday Access, in Weights room
description:
In the arena of life, only the determined, the disciplined, and the powerful prove their mettle. Our Powerlifting Club isn’t just about lifting weights; it's about lifting each other, as well as ourselves, up. Here, strength isn’t just physical — it’s META-PHYSICAL(!), a commitment to equity, community, and constitution. 

In the vast spectrum of high school sports, it's time for powerlifting to claim its throne. Through our Powerlifting Club, we don't just champion the art of lifting weights but the spirit of lifting each other higher. In this arena of life, where determination, discipline, and raw power intertwine, our mission is more than just physical strength. It's a META-PHYSICAL endeavor! We pledge ourselves to principles of equity, community, and unwavering constitution. As we drive forward our vision to embed powerlifting in high schools nationwide, we are passionately committed to empowering teens, granting them not only muscles of steel but also the willpower and confidence that come with it.
description_summary: The Powerlifting Club is dedicated to more than just physical strength; it promotes equity, community, and unwavering constitution. It seeks to elevate both individuals and the sport of powerlifting in high schools across the nation, fostering determination, discipline, and empowerment among teens.

name: Presidential Volunteer Service Award
meeting: second Friday of every month
description: The Presidential Volunteer Service Award club is a distinguished national organization that celebrates and honors the outstanding contributions of volunteers who are dedicated to enhancing their communities through selfless service. Members participate in various volunteer events to help local organizations. We aim to inspire others to make a positive impact.
description_summary: The Presidential Volunteer Service Award club is a distinguished national organization that celebrates and honors the outstanding contributions of volunteers who are dedicated to enhancing their communities through selfless service. Members participate in various volunteer events to help local organizations. We aim to inspire others to make a positive impact.

name: Product Design
meeting: Twice a month, every other Monday, room 4105
description: Our club aims to educate students on the world of Product Design, ranging from User Experience Design to prototyping and creating real-life products. By exciting students with interactive activities, which teach them the fundamental ideas and values of the design process, students will adopt the skillset to design and build products that will make a positive impact on the community. We want to increase awareness of Product Design and the pathways that it leads to. We also want to fuse the worlds of engineering and design, to provide students with new opportunities. We strive to create an inclusive, social environment where students who are interested in STEM can bond and make lifelong friendships. Our club would like to give back to our community by building useful products, and we aim to make an impact in our community for years to come.
description_summary: The club focuses on educating students about Product Design, covering User Experience Design, prototyping, and real-life product creation through interactive activities. The goal is to equip students with design skills to create community-beneficial products, raise awareness about Product Design, and bridge the gap between engineering and design. The club aims to foster an inclusive, social environment for STEM enthusiasts to form lasting friendships and contribute to the community through impactful product development.

name: Project C.A.R.E.
meeting: Twice a month, on the second and fourth Thursday, in Room 2106
description: Project C.A.R.E is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization specializing in donating first aid, medical, and hygiene supplies to underserved new mothers and children. Our mission is to educate mothers in underprivileged communities through donations and partnerships with health institutions to disperse essential educational materials.
description_summary: Project C.A.R.E is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization specializing in donating first aid, medical, and hygiene supplies to underserved new mothers and children. Our mission is to educate mothers in underprivileged communities through donations and partnerships with health institutions to disperse essential educational materials.

name: Project Morph
meeting: once a month in room 1118, either on the last thursday or friday of the month.
description: Project Morph is a student-led non-profit that creates jewelry, hosts events, runs donation drives, and raises funds through all of that in order to give back to the domestic violence survivors in the Bay Area. Along with helping out, we also aim to spread awareness on our campus about domestic violence, and its influence in our society. Students get to be hands on with hosting events, creating the jewelry, and helping create care packages for the shelters as well.
description_summary: Project Morph is a student-led non-profit in the Bay Area that creates jewelry, hosts events, runs donation drives, and raises funds to support domestic violence survivors. They focus on hands-on activities such as hosting events, crafting jewelry, and creating care packages for shelters while also raising awareness about domestic violence on campus.

name: Radios and Aerospace
meeting: 1-2 times a month, on Wednesday, in room 4207
description: Formed in 2019, the Radios and Aerospace club aims to interest people into joining the growing aerospace and aeronautical industry through a combination of interactive lessons, engaging activities, and a hands-on yearlong project. Noteworthy projects made in previous years include DVHS's first high altitude balloon launch, model rocket launches, and a custom-built drone.
description_summary: Formed in 2019, the Radios and Aerospace club aims to interest people into joining the growing aerospace and aeronautical industry through a combination of interactive lessons, engaging activities, and a hands-on yearlong project. Noteworthy projects made in previous years include DVHS's first high altitude balloon launch, model rocket launches, and a custom-built drone.

name: Reel Stories
meeting: Weekly, every Friday, room 9110
description: DVHS Reel Stories is a club dedicated to provide a platform for students interested in filmmaking.  Throughout the year, students are taught about the various stages of the filmmaking, such as scriptwriting, cinematography, and post-production as they pursue their very own projects to present for peers at the end of the academic year.  DVHS Reel Stories strives to promote filmmaking to people of all backgrounds to encourage diversity in the film industry.
description_summary: DVHS Reel Stories is a club that fosters filmmaking passion among students. It offers hands-on learning in scriptwriting, cinematography, and post-production, culminating in project presentations at year-end. The club's mission is to promote diversity in the film industry by welcoming students from all backgrounds.

name: Reflection Resilience Alliance
meeting: Once a month on the last wednesday of every month, in room 4207
description: The Reflection Resilience Alliance is a safe environment where we discuss self-image and body positivity, as well as ways for navigating the challenges of societal norms.
description_summary: The Reflection Resilience Alliance is a safe environment where we discuss self-image and body positivity, as well as ways for navigating the challenges of societal norms.

name: Robotics
meeting: Every Monday and Friday, 4-6PM, in room 4221
description: The DVHS Robotics Club was founded in 2007 and has since been devoted to the pursuit of robotics and other STEM-related areas. Through the years, we have participated in numerous competitions, gradually developing our knowledge about the VEX platform. Our club is now one of the largest on-campus, supporting 100+ members of all grades and experience.  A new member applying freshman year can expect to first join a novice team and spend a year learning about robotics (both general and VEX specific), mechanical/electrical engineering concepts, and computer science. During this time, the member will be able to learn about various components of a robot, such as drive trains, lifts, and object manipulators, while working on hands-on projects and participating in competitions with other novice teams in the club. Throughout the year, our club has earned 120+ awards qualifying for state and international championships every year, and have even become Division Champions on the International level at the VEX Worlds Competition in Dallas, Texas.
description_summary: The DVHS Robotics Club, founded in 2007, is dedicated to robotics and STEM pursuits. With 100+ members, including novices, it offers hands-on learning in robotics, engineering, and computer science. Members work on projects, compete with novice teams, and have achieved 120+ awards, including Division Champions at VEX Worlds in Dallas, Texas.

name: Robotics First Tech Challenge
meeting: Every other Friday online after school.
description: First Tech Challenge is a competitive robotics program under the non-profit organization FIRST. FTC focuses on developing skills within the STEM fields by programming and building robots which are used to participate in competitions hosted by FTC going head to head in an alliance based format game completing various challenges that require creative and ingenuity. Additionally, FTC spreads STEM within their community and participate in volunteering to spread their knowledge.
description_summary: First Tech Challenge (FTC) is a competitive robotics program by FIRST, a non-profit. FTC focuses on STEM skills through robot programming and building for competitions. Teams compete in alliance-based games, tackling creative challenges. FTC also promotes STEM in the community through volunteering and knowledge sharing.

name: Sankara Eye Foundation
meeting: Every Wednesday during lunch; room 1211
description: The Dougherty Valley High School Sankara Eye Foundation Club is associated with the Sankara Eye Foundation. This club supports the Sankara Eye Foundation’s mission of eradicating curable blindness in India through fundraising. Through this club, you can gain valuable experience through the internship program where you contact previous donors and update them on the organization’s current plans. You can also participate in various fundraising activities such as the Facebook Fundraiser to raise money towards the free eye surgeries the Sankara Eye Foundation performs. If you’re looking to get involved in a club that offers volunteering experience and the opportunity to gain various skills, join the Dougherty Valley High School Sankara Eye Foundation Club!
description_summary: The Dougherty Valley High School Sankara Eye Foundation Club supports the Sankara Eye Foundation's mission to eradicate curable blindness in India through fundraising activities. Members can participate in an internship program involving donor outreach and engage in fundraisers like the Facebook Fundraiser to support free eye surgeries. Join for volunteering experience and skill development opportunities.

name: Save the Birdies
meeting: Last Monday of the month in room 4212
description: The goal of the Save the Birdies club is to introduce the sport of badminton to new players and help teach them the basics and establish a good foundation. We also plan on helping hone the skills of more advanced players by having the opportunity to play against others and correcting the mistakes that they make. We intend on going to badminton gyms and using that opportunity to play amongst ourselves as well as playing against others also there. At the end of the year, we will host a badminton tournament with neighboring schools to see how far we've grown. Also, we will have fundraisers that helps make the club more enjoyable and helpful for all members. Our hope is that we can show new people the sport that's brought joy to so many and to make badminton soar to new heights within DVHS.
description_summary: The Save the Birdies club aims to introduce badminton to new players, teach them the basics, and improve the skills of advanced players. Activities include playing at gyms, hosting a year-end tournament with neighboring schools, and organizing fundraisers for club enhancement. The goal is to promote the sport and its growth at DVHS.

name: Science Alliance
meeting: 1st Monday of every month, starting from October to March in the Commons. Additional meetings are the last Wednesday of every month in room 2101.
description: Founded with a mission to introduce elementary school students to investigative science and methodical inquiry, Science Alliance pairs motivated elementary school students with high school mentors (from Monte Vista, San Ramon Valley, Dougherty Valley, & California High Schools), who teach the scientific process while guiding the students through original science fair projects. Both the kids and mentors commit to this yearlong program that helps prepare the kids for middle and high school lab science and gives the mentors the opportunity to act as positive role models for younger students. Fifth grade buddies get the opportunity to present their hard work at an end-of-the-year science fair! Please visit our website for more information: http://www.dvhssciencealliance.com/
description_summary: Science Alliance is a program that pairs motivated elementary school students with high school mentors to explore investigative science. It guides students through science fair projects, preparing them for future lab science. The year-long program fosters mentorship and ends with a science fair where fifth graders showcase their work.

name: Science National Honor Society
meeting: Our club will likely meet on the last Wednesday of every month. We will send information about the meeting, times, and location through email and Remind. To join Remind, text @dvhssnh to 81010
description: To join, text @dvhssnh to 81010. The Science National Honor Society works to combat educational inequalities in STEM industries by providing access to tutoring resources, assistance for summer programs, as well mentoring students for local science fairs, in order to make STEM more accessible for all. Our goals for this club is to encourage scientific thought and advance students’ knowledge of science, communicate with the scientific community, aid students with their comprehension of science, and encourage scientific knowledge as per the charter of the Science National Honor Society. SNHS fosters member interest in science and encourages future careers in STEM by gathering together high-achieving, science-oriented students. Through various programs and activities, the SNHS strives to inspire students to pursue a career in science and provide them with the skills and knowledge they need to succeed in the field.
description_summary: The Science National Honor Society (SNHS) focuses on combatting educational inequalities in STEM by offering tutoring, summer program support, and mentoring for science fairs. Their goals include promoting scientific thought, communication with the scientific community, aiding comprehension of science, and encouraging scientific careers. SNHS gathers high-achieving, science-oriented students to inspire them to pursue careers in STEM through various programs and activities.

name: Science Olympiad
meeting: Every week, on Friday, room 2209
description: The Science Olympiad Club helps students explore new science and technology topics and study them at a higher level. It is affiliated with the nationwide Science Olympiad competition where teams can compete against other schools at the regional, state, and national levels. Each team consists of 15 members who compete in 23 different events in life science, earth science, tech and engineering, physics and chemistry, and inquiry of science. The club holds tryouts at the start of the year and meets weekly to prepare and study for competitions.
description_summary: The Science Olympiad Club offers students the opportunity to delve into various science and technology subjects and participate in the nationwide Science Olympiad competition. Teams, comprising 15 members, compete in 23 diverse events covering life science, earth science, tech and engineering, physics, and chemistry. The club conducts tryouts annually and holds weekly meetings for competition preparation.

name: SEWA
meeting: Once a month, last tuesday of the month, in room 2101
description: The purpose of the DVHS Sewa Club is to bring the humanitarian, service based club to campus. As Californians, we are no strangers to the disasters that occur on a daily basis and that is what Sewa specializes in, disaster relief and rehabilitation. In addition to this, Sewa plays a large role in mitigating issues worldwide such as family and child welfare and promoting education. As the DVHS chapter of this organization, we can do our part in helping this organization accomplish its goals. Our goal as the DVHS chapter of Sewa would be to choose a few issues that we resonate with and work alongside Sewa to do our part. However, our overall goal would be to make an impact on the lives of the people in this world who are less fortunate than we are. At the end of each semester, we expect to have 2 deliverables complete, this includes, but is not limited to projects centered around disaster relief, fights against period poverty, and more. Beyond this, the goal of the DVHS Sewa Club would be to give members opportunities to take on leadership positions and gain confidence as they work in group environments.
description_summary: The DVHS Sewa Club's primary focus is on humanitarian activities, disaster relief, family and child welfare, and education promotion. They aim to collaborate with Sewa to address these global issues. Each semester, they plan to complete 2 projects related to disaster relief, period poverty, and more. Additionally, the club provides leadership opportunities for members to gain confidence in group settings.

name: Spanish
meeting: Once a week, on the second Tuesday, in room 3202
description: Spanish Club helps our members understand the cultural values of the Spanish culture.  We celebrate an important Spanish event for every month that we meet.  We want people to be able to love the Spanish cultures even if they do not understand the language.  There is beauty in every part of the world and this is one part that we are excited to share.
description_summary: The Spanish Club focuses on promoting Spanish culture through monthly cultural events and celebrations. It aims to foster an appreciation for Spanish traditions and values, irrespective of language barriers, with a goal of sharing the beauty of Spanish culture with its members.

name: Speech and Debate
meeting: Once a month, last Wednesday of month, DVHS Commons
description: Dougherty Valley was recently awarded the School of Excellence Award in Debate at the NSDA National Tournament, making us one of the Top 10 programs in the National Speech and Debate Association. Incredible coaches, dedicated students, and countless hours of preparation come together to create Dougherty Valley Speech and Debate, and in our club, we strive to foster communication, confidence, and critical thinking skills in our students, all while achieving competitive success along the way.
description_summary: Dougherty Valley's Speech and Debate Club recently achieved the School of Excellence Award at the NSDA National Tournament, ranking among the Top 10 programs nationally. The club emphasizes communication, confidence, and critical thinking skills, with dedicated students and coaches who invest numerous hours in preparation for competitive success.

name: Sports Medicine
meeting: Once a month, third thursday, in room 1111
description: DVHS Sports Medicine club is dedicated to teaching students all about injury precautions and safety in the sports world and day to day life. We learn a variety of different skills such as applying splints and tape, treating heat-related illnesses, and more! We welcome everyone interested in sports medicine or any type of health care career.
description_summary: DVHS Sports Medicine club is dedicated to teaching students all about injury precautions and safety in the sports world and day to day life. We learn a variety of different skills such as applying splints and tape, treating heat-related illnesses, and more! We welcome everyone interested in sports medicine or any type of health care career.

name: Spread The Colors
meeting: Twice a month, every other wednesday, in Mrs.Reynold's room
description: The goal of our club is to help kids with special needs live a carefree and fun lifestyle. We plan on doing this by bringing arts and crafts to kids with special needs in Windemere Ranch Middle School. By arts and crafts we plan on bringing painting supplies, origami paper, and a mix of assorted crafts to leave a long lasting impact on these kids at least once a month. Furthermore, We want to spend time with kids with special needs. Our club is mainly targeted to help make these kids feel included in many things and in their school. In addition, this will also create an environment for bonding. We will help them get to know each other and have conversations with each other. This is a great club that could also help kids in general with their socialization skills. This club can also be a beneficiary because we can help kids that have special needs make a lot more new friends. We wanted to create a way for them to be comfortable while also helping them relieve their stress. This not only makes our experience doing arts and crafts fun but also a safe environment for kids to let loose and socialize. This is also a great project for both two schools, Dougherty Valley and Windemere Ranch to come together. Our main focus is making everyone feel included whether they have special needs or not. In addition, The special ed students will feel more welcomed in the community and will be able to talk to many people while also building their skills as artists!
description_summary: The club's primary goal is to engage kids with special needs from Windemere Ranch Middle School in creative activities. The emphasis is on fostering inclusion, bonding, and socialization among these students. The club aims to unite students from Dougherty Valley and Windemere Ranch, creating a welcoming community for all, with a focus on enhancing the artistic skills of special education students.

name: Stories R Us
meeting: Twice a month, every other Tuesday during lunch, in room 3204
description: Stories R Us is a club that collaborates with elementary school students and encourages creativity through the design of storybooks! Members work together to develop unique Mad-Lib style story templates that are sent to elementary students to fill in and illustrate corresponding pictures for!
